<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06019031 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06019031 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; AP File Photograph; Gorbachev is losing key advisers  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  USSR; PRESIDENT; REACTION; ETHNIC; STATE; VIOLENCE; PUBLIC; OPINION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Mikhail Gorbachev's crackdown on separatism in the Baltic states haskindled long-smoldering discontent into a blaze of censure by Sovietjournalists, intellectuals and reform-minded bureaucrats who once were hismain supporters.;    Statement after statement denouncing Gorbachev forordering tanks and troops into Vilnius, the Lithuanian capital, on Sunday isbeing published in the Soviet press by intellectuals who were hailing theSoviet leader five years ago as their liberator. Even some of his formeradvisers have signed.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EX-SUPPORTERS CENSURING GORBACHEV AFTER CRACKDOWN  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Eduard Shevardnadze, thought to have been one of his closest politicaladvisers, resigned Dec. 20 and warned against the approach of &quot;dictatorship.&quot;;   This week some Soviet Foreign Ministry officials made little secret oftheir revulsion not only at the loss of life in Lithuania but also at theofficial propaganda trying to justify what the army did.;    Disillusionedintelligentsia;  Though the Soviet intelligentsia has been growing steadilymore disillusioned with the president over the past year or so, the assault bytroops on unarmed civilians in Lithuania, in which at least 14 people died,has sent many intellectuals into outright opposition.;    On Wednesday,Gorbachev angrily cited a declaration by 30 intellectuals published in theweekly Moscow News that day and briefly suggested that the Soviet legislaturetemporarily suspend the press law that forbids censorship.;    Two of hisformer economic advisers, Nikolai Petrakov and Stanislav Shatalin, are amongthe prestigious list of writers, journalists and other members of thenewspaper's founding board who signed the statement, which criticized thepresident directly.;    Writers condemn action;  Anatoly Rybakov, the80-year-old novelist whom Gorbachev allowed in 1987 to publish &quot;Children ofthe Arbat,&quot; the chronicle of Stalin's terror, headed another list of 47writers who signed a declaration on Thursday condemning the action inLithuania.;    The letter, bearing the signatures of such other well-knownmembers of the Russian-Soviet Pen Center as the poet Andrei Voznesensky, is tobe published next week in the weekly Literaturnaya Gazeta.;    Vadim Bakatin,who as Gorbachev's interior minister was in charge of the national policeuntil his replacement by Boris Pugo on Dec. 1, said of the decision to sendthe army in against civilians in Vilnius, &quot;The illegality andunconstitutionality of actions as a result of which people were killed areobvious.&quot;;    Pugo justified the army's involvement without regret on Mondayas a response to violence by armed civilians.;    Influential papers;  Manynewspapers here and Soviet television, the dominant medium, faithfully reflectthe government version of events, but there are important, influential paperslike Komsomolskaya Pravda that do not.;    Shatalin, the economist whose500-day plan to create a free-market economy Gorbachev rejected in October,told Moscow News this week, &quot;I no longer consider myself a 'player' inGorbachev's team.&quot;;    Gorbachev may not have considered him one either, sinceShatalin signed an open letter in November, after his 500-day plan wasrejected, warning of hyperinflation and political paralysis.;    Theseriousness of fears among people like this about a return to dictatorshipsank in on the West when Shevardnadze resigned.;    Not all of Gorbachev'scritics agree that he has succumbed to the temptations of dictatorship, butthey agree that by giving the army free rein last weekend, he made asignificant lurch to the right.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  CRAIG R. WHITNEY, New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Moscow  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910119  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  551  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday January 19, 199100019031,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>